body:
As discussed with @mmicko, these changes will reduce the number of CPEs to realize fixed values at the block RAM inputs, if not used.

_What are the reasons/motivation for this change?_

In order to realize fixed values such as zero clamping at the block RAM inputs, we must insert additional CPEs. In many cases, however, these are superfluous: If, for example, a `CC_BRAM_20K` is only configured for a data bus width of 5 bits, the upper bits [15:5] are ignored and do not need to be assigned with zeros.

_Explain how this is achieved._

We change `{A,B}_{BM,DI}` for all `CC_BRAM_{20K,40K}` in `techlibs/gatemate/brams_map.v` to fill the upper bits with `'x`.

_If applicable, please suggest to reviewers how they can test the change._

```
// Single Port RAM (NO_CHANGE)
module bram_sp_nc (input we, clk, input [9:0] di, input [7:0] addr, output reg [9:0] dox);
  reg [9:0] memory [0:2**8-1];

  always @(posedge clk) begin
    if (we)
      memory[addr] <= di;
    else
      dox <= memory[addr];
  end
endmodule
```

Results in`10'hxxx` being placed before the data bus and bit enable mask instead of `10'h000`:

```
// ...
CC_BRAM_20K #(
// ...
  .A_BM({ 10'hxxx, _07_, _07_, _07_, _07_, _07_, _07_, _07_, _07_, _07_, _07_ }),
  .A_DI({ 10'hxxx, _05_ }),
// ...
```

